sed to be many more. Also, there are no significant reclamation efforts underway or pedagogical resources for learning the language, Mapudungun. This is because in Chile's rigid class structure, Mapuches are seen as the lowest class. Because of this, it is not uncommon for Mapuches to change their names to sound Chilean, or for parents to not teach their children Mapudungun.%0a%3c %0a%3c Because of this, in urban areas Mapudungun is spoken mostly ceremoniously during cultural celebrations involving dancing and music. There is still a stigma associated with being Mapuche.%0a%3c %0a%3c Only in rural areas where the Mapuche live in relatively isolated reserves is Mapundungun spoken in daily life.%0a%3c %0a%3c Although there are many Mapuches living in South America, there is no reliable information about how many speakers there are. Potentially because some speakers do not want to make their ancestry public.%0a%3c %0a%3c From research done on other websites one important difference I have found is that the websites run by Mapuches focus much more on the present: how certain laws are unjust, how the stigma of being Mapuche still persists. Other non-Mapuche sources, however, focus more on the past and what the Mapuche tribe used to be. This difference in the time period sources focus on is harmful to the Mapuche because it makes it seem like the tribe is extinct.%0a%3c %0a%3c sources: https://www.mapuche.nl %0a%3c https://theculturetrip.com/south-america/chile/articles/a-brief-history-of-chiles-indigenous-mapuche-people/%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
